ote:

These dynamics were in many respects the same as the advertising dynamics I=
 described above: on Facebook both small companies and large companies have=
 an equal shot at customers, and both Party insiders and complete outsiders=
 have an equal shot at voters. Moreover, it=E2=80=99s a dynamic that is eve=
n greater when combined: Trump famously used Facebook advertising to far gr=
eater effect than the Clinton campaign. And, at the same time, the New York=
 Times, itself demoted to another attention seeker in a Facebook world, fam=
ously spent huge amounts of time on Clinton=E2=80=99s emails.

What seems clear in retrospect is that the latter two entities made peace (=
and avoided introspection) by making Facebook the scapegoat for Trump=E2=80=
=99s election. This was true in a way =E2=80=94 Facebook created the condit=
ions for someone like Trump to win =E2=80=94 but the furor that followed su=
ggested something much more explicit: within days the conversation was abou=
t Fake News and Russian influence being the key factors, not campaign mista=
kes and questionable coverage decisions, and certainly not the fundamental =
way that the media environment had changed.

This was a narrative that Zuckerberg and most of tech went along with (Zuck=
erberg would soon apologize for the comments above): over the next few year=
s the company specifically and tech generally devoted massive amounts of re=
sources towards building up huge moderation apparatuses and became dramatic=
ally more aggressive about censoring alleged misinformation; this effort re=
ached its apotheosis during COVID and the 2020 election, including Facebook=
 and Twitter censoring the Hunter Biden laptop story. I noted in an October=
 2020 Update ( https://stratechery.com/2020/tech-in-congress-again-twitter-=
vs-the-new-york-post-who-are-the-refs/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsI=
