ift in tech we are seeing =E2=80=94 and to be clear, Musk and Andreessen Ho=
rowitz are on the vanguard, as the industry remains almost entirely Democra=
tic =E2=80=94 is not so much about actively supporting President Trump and =
opposing President Biden as it is about a shift from a position of politica=
l inertness to active self interest. Horowitz said at the beginning of that=
 podcast:

So one of the reasons we=E2=80=99re doing this podcast is there are people =
who know much more about foreign policy or the various groups rights issues=
 or economic theory or all kinds of stuff than we do, but when it comes to =
startups and the policies around them, there=E2=80=99s maybe one or two oth=
er people at our level of expertise in the whole world just because, you kn=
ow, we do it all day long. We work with startups. We see the impact of the =
policies. And then we=E2=80=99ve been in Washington doing a lot of work. An=
d so that that kind of brings us to the reason for the podcast=E2=80=A6

And at the end:

This is the last thing I wanted. In fact, you know, one, I didn=E2=80=99t w=
ant us to get into politics. We kind of got dragged into it. You know, my f=
ather has been in politics. I can say personally, I watched him lose all of=
 his friends when he switched political sides. It was really an uncanny exp=
erience when I was a kid. And the last thing I wanted for the firm, for our=
 employees, for the companies we invest in and so forth, was us to be invol=
ved in this because it gets very emotional and it=E2=80=99s tough.

But like we literally, like the future of our business, the future of techn=
ology, new technology, and the future of America is literally at stake with=
 some of these I just say like really misguided and difficult policies. So =
here we are. And for a little tech, we think Donald Trump is actually the r=
ight choice.

What Horowitz says about the pain of switching sides and losing friends is =
important: I have criticized tech companies for alienating their natural al=
lies in Washington, but what I am driving at in this Update is the extent t=
o which the Democrats generally and the media specifically have made a simi=
lar error; by making tech the scapegoat for Trump, =E2=80=9Cthe deal=E2=80=
=9D that united tech and Democrats was broken. The end result is not so muc=
h enmity as it is naked self interest. In other words, the surprise isn=E2=
=80=99t that Musk and Andreessen and Horowitz are supporting the politician=
 that is better for their business ventures, but that Democrats gave up the=
 enviable position of being the default choice for people who didn=E2=80=99=
t want to think about politics at all.

